00:07:14.600 --> 00:07:17.700
And I'm super excited to be
able to share with you today

00:07:17.700 --> 00:07:19.960
a couple quick lessons
from my new book,

00:07:19.960 --> 00:07:21.840
"Storytelling with Data."

00:07:21.840 --> 00:07:24.450
So we're going to talk
today about two key lessons,

00:07:24.450 --> 00:07:27.692
first off, focusing attention,
and secondly, telling a story.

00:07:27.692 --> 00:07:29.400
We want to draw one
important distinction

00:07:29.400 --> 00:07:31.024
at this point, which
is the distinction

00:07:31.024 --> 00:07:35.450
between exploratory analysis
and explanatory analysis.

00:07:35.450 --> 00:07:37.420
So exploratory analysis,
you perhaps start off

00:07:37.420 --> 00:07:39.375
with a question or
hypothesis, or you're just

00:07:39.375 --> 00:07:40.750
digging through
your data, trying

00:07:40.750 --> 00:07:42.470
to understand
what's interesting,

00:07:42.470 --> 00:07:45.550
what can I learn about this
data that somebody else

00:07:45.550 --> 00:07:47.220
might care about?

00:07:47.220 --> 00:07:49.690
Once you've identified
that interesting thing,

00:07:49.690 --> 00:07:52.200
then we move into
explanatory space.

00:07:52.200 --> 00:07:54.710
That is where you have
something specific

00:07:54.710 --> 00:07:58.400
you want to communicate
to somebody specific.

00:07:58.400 --> 00:08:02.630
And it's this latter space we
want to keep in mind today.

00:08:02.630 --> 00:08:05.020
And when it comes to
explanatory analysis,

00:08:05.020 --> 00:08:07.680
these lessons become more
important than perhaps

00:08:07.680 --> 00:08:10.630
any others-- first off,
thinking about where

00:08:10.630 --> 00:08:12.590
you want your audience
to pay attention

00:08:12.590 --> 00:08:16.380
and doing things on purpose
to make that happen,

00:08:16.380 --> 00:08:19.700
and then secondly, never
simply showing data, but rather

00:08:19.700 --> 00:08:23.470
making data a pivotal point
in an overarching story.

00:08:23.470 --> 00:08:25.680
So we'll talk briefly
through each of these.

00:08:25.680 --> 00:08:27.780
First off, focusing
attention-- I

00:08:27.780 --> 00:08:30.030
can recall a time at
Google where I was working

00:08:30.030 --> 00:08:31.579
on the Project Oxygen study.

00:08:31.579 --> 00:08:33.120
Quick show of hands--
how many people

00:08:33.120 --> 00:08:35.151
are familiar with
Project Oxygen?

00:08:35.151 --> 00:08:36.150
Most people in the room.

00:08:36.150 --> 00:08:40.140
So Project Oxygen was a study
led by my colleague Neil Patel.

00:08:40.140 --> 00:08:43.280
And the goal really was
to try to understand,

00:08:43.280 --> 00:08:45.990
on a mathematical,
statistical level,

00:08:45.990 --> 00:08:48.772
what makes managers effective.

00:08:48.772 --> 00:08:50.480
One of the challenges
that we encountered

00:08:50.480 --> 00:08:53.980
was, after the study was done,
communicating the results of it

00:08:53.980 --> 00:08:57.440
to a very mixed audience, where
we had both engineers, who

00:08:57.440 --> 00:09:00.084
had a great desire for detail--
they wanted to understand

00:09:00.084 --> 00:09:01.500
the methodology,
they wanted to be

00:09:01.500 --> 00:09:03.877
convinced of the
robustness of the analysis.

00:09:03.877 --> 00:09:05.460
At the same time,
we were also wanting

00:09:05.460 --> 00:09:07.480
to communicate to
sales managers,

00:09:07.480 --> 00:09:10.910
for example, who were mostly
less concerned with methodology

00:09:10.910 --> 00:09:13.200
and more concerned about
what's in it for me.

00:09:13.200 --> 00:09:15.600
How should I act
differently based on this?

00:09:15.600 --> 00:09:18.920
And so what we found was by
really being careful about how

00:09:18.920 --> 00:09:22.410
we focused attention, we could
preserve a lot of that detail

00:09:22.410 --> 00:09:25.430
but push it to the background
and make the meta-point pop

00:09:25.430 --> 00:09:27.865
out so that it was clear.

00:09:27.865 --> 00:09:29.240
Let's talk a little
bit about how

00:09:29.240 --> 00:09:33.700
people see to get into more of
this how we focus attention.

00:09:33.700 --> 00:09:36.999
So here's a super-simplified
picture of that process.

00:09:36.999 --> 00:09:39.165
On the left-hand side, you
have light refracting off

00:09:39.165 --> 00:09:39.990
a stimulus.

00:09:39.990 --> 00:09:41.760
This gets captured by our eyes.

00:09:41.760 --> 00:09:43.610
We don't fully
see with our eyes.

00:09:43.610 --> 00:09:45.960
Rather, most of what we
think of as visual processing

00:09:45.960 --> 00:09:47.790
takes place in our brains.

00:09:47.790 --> 00:09:50.080
Now, in the brains there
are a few types of memory

00:09:50.080 --> 00:09:52.360
that are important to
understand as we're designing

00:09:52.360 --> 00:09:53.520
visual communications.

00:09:53.520 --> 00:09:57.380
We'll talk about one of them
today, which is iconic memory.

00:09:57.380 --> 00:09:59.390
Iconic memory is
super short-term.

00:09:59.390 --> 00:10:00.890
It's shorter than
short-term memory,

00:10:00.890 --> 00:10:03.640
and information stays there
for fractions of a second

00:10:03.640 --> 00:10:06.760
before it gets forwarded on
to our short-term memory.

00:10:06.760 --> 00:10:08.890
The really cool thing
about iconic memory

00:10:08.890 --> 00:10:10.900
is that it's tuned to a
specific set of what we

00:10:10.900 --> 00:10:13.290
call pre-attentive attributes.

00:10:13.290 --> 00:10:16.180
So let's actually pause here
and do a quick exercise.

00:10:16.180 --> 00:10:18.990
So in a moment, I'm going
to put a bunch of numbers

00:10:18.990 --> 00:10:20.430
up on the screen.

00:10:20.430 --> 00:10:22.790
What I'd like you all
to do as fast as you can

00:10:22.790 --> 00:10:25.060
is count the number
of 3s that you see.

00:10:25.060 --> 00:10:25.560
We got it?

00:10:25.560 --> 00:10:26.930
We're going to count 3s.

00:10:26.930 --> 00:10:29.730
When you know the
answer, shout it out.

00:10:29.730 --> 00:10:31.070
It is a race.

00:10:31.070 --> 00:10:32.451
You would like to win.

00:10:32.451 --> 00:10:33.894
Ready, set, go!

00:10:42.560 --> 00:10:44.930
All right, six is
the correct answer.

00:10:44.930 --> 00:10:46.870
This took a bit of
time, though, right?

00:10:46.870 --> 00:10:49.070
You had to physically
read through these four

00:10:49.070 --> 00:10:50.890
lines of text,
look for a 3, which

00:10:50.890 --> 00:10:52.910
is kind of a complicated shape.

00:10:52.910 --> 00:10:54.700
Watch what a
different exercise it

00:10:54.700 --> 00:10:58.699
becomes when I make
one tiny change.

00:10:58.699 --> 00:10:59.740
Don't have time to think.

00:10:59.740 --> 00:11:00.781
Don't have time to blink.

00:11:00.781 --> 00:11:03.790
Suddenly there are six
3s in front of you.

00:11:03.790 --> 00:11:05.890
This is so apparent
so quickly because I'm

00:11:05.890 --> 00:11:07.800
leveraging your iconic memory.

00:11:07.800 --> 00:11:09.580
I'm using the
pre-attentive attribute

00:11:09.580 --> 00:11:12.000
of intensity of
color, in this case,

00:11:12.000 --> 00:11:14.890
to make the 3s the one
thing that stand out as

00:11:14.890 --> 00:11:16.440
different from the rest.

00:11:16.440 --> 00:11:19.130
Now, this is hugely critical,
because what this means is

00:11:19.130 --> 00:11:22.320
our pre-attentive attributes,
if we use them strategically,

00:11:22.320 --> 00:11:24.720
can help enable us
to get our audience

00:11:24.720 --> 00:11:27.420
to see what we want them
to see before they even

00:11:27.420 --> 00:11:30.050
know they're seeing it.

00:11:30.050 --> 00:11:32.084
Here are the attributes.

00:11:32.084 --> 00:11:33.500
I won't read through
all of these,

00:11:33.500 --> 00:11:36.690
but notice as your eyes
scan across the screen

00:11:36.690 --> 00:11:38.119
how they're just
drawn to the one

00:11:38.119 --> 00:11:40.160
within each group that's
different from the rest.

00:11:40.160 --> 00:11:43.550
You don't really have to
consciously look for it.

00:11:43.550 --> 00:11:45.690
Now, one thing to know
about the attributes

00:11:45.690 --> 00:11:47.930
is people tend to associate
quantitative values

00:11:47.930 --> 00:11:49.960
with some but not others.

00:11:49.960 --> 00:11:52.700
For example, most people
will consider a long line

00:11:52.700 --> 00:11:55.260
to represent a greater
value than a short line.

00:11:55.260 --> 00:11:57.270
It's one of the
reasons bar charts are

00:11:57.270 --> 00:11:58.810
intuitive for us to read.

00:11:58.810 --> 00:12:02.360
But we don't think of hue,
for example, in the same way.

00:12:02.360 --> 00:12:04.200
If I ask you which is
greater, red or blue,

00:12:04.200 --> 00:12:06.360
it's not really a
meaningful question.

00:12:06.360 --> 00:12:08.160
And this is important
because it tells us

00:12:08.160 --> 00:12:10.110
which of the
attributes can be used

00:12:10.110 --> 00:12:13.130
in code quantitative information
and which should be used

00:12:13.130 --> 00:12:15.890
as categorical differentiators.

00:12:15.890 --> 00:12:18.450
Now as you can perhaps imagine,
pre-attentive attributes

00:12:18.450 --> 00:12:22.560
become huge tools for focusing
our audience's attention when

00:12:22.560 --> 00:12:24.830
it comes to visualizing data.

00:12:24.830 --> 00:12:27.900
So here's some sort of generic
data from our annual customer

00:12:27.900 --> 00:12:28.730
survey.

00:12:28.730 --> 00:12:32.410
We can see how we've fared
across a number of dimensions.

00:12:32.410 --> 00:12:36.390
Notice how without other visual
cues, this becomes very much

00:12:36.390 --> 00:12:38.870
like the count-the-3s
example again.

00:12:38.870 --> 00:12:41.210
We have to look at this
data, read through it,

00:12:41.210 --> 00:12:44.240
figure out what might be
important to pay attention to.

00:12:44.240 --> 00:12:46.970
Whereas if I'm the one
communicating this data,

00:12:46.970 --> 00:12:50.200
I should have already done
that for you, in which case

00:12:50.200 --> 00:12:52.990
I can use some pre-attentive
attributes, perhaps paired

00:12:52.990 --> 00:12:55.810
with some explanatory text,
to draw your attention very

00:12:55.810 --> 00:12:58.259
quickly to one part
of the story, right?

00:12:58.259 --> 00:13:00.300
Price and convenience--
we're doing awesome here.

00:13:00.300 --> 00:13:03.050
Let's pause and
celebrate our success.

00:13:03.050 --> 00:13:04.850
Or I can use this
same broad strategy

00:13:04.850 --> 00:13:07.270
to draw your attention to
a totally different place

00:13:07.270 --> 00:13:08.340
in the data.

00:13:08.340 --> 00:13:09.790
But we're struggling
when it comes

00:13:09.790 --> 00:13:11.460
to relationship and brand.

00:13:11.460 --> 00:13:15.520
How can we positively
impact these areas?

00:13:15.520 --> 00:13:19.580
Now, there's a test I like to
employ in trying to figure out

00:13:19.580 --> 00:13:21.780
whether you're using your
pre-attentive attributes

00:13:21.780 --> 00:13:22.820
strategically.

00:13:22.820 --> 00:13:25.730
And that is the Where
Are Your Eyes Drawn Test,

00:13:25.730 --> 00:13:28.320
where you look away from your
visual and look back at it,

00:13:28.320 --> 00:13:30.130
or close your eyes
and look back at it,

00:13:30.130 --> 00:13:33.170
and just notice where
your eyes land first.

00:13:33.170 --> 00:13:35.770
Because it's probably
where your audience's eyes

00:13:35.770 --> 00:13:37.330
will land as well.

00:13:37.330 --> 00:13:40.161
So I thought we'd do this
with a series of pictures

00:13:40.161 --> 00:13:41.660
and just talk about
the implications

00:13:41.660 --> 00:13:42.770
for our visual designs.

00:13:42.770 --> 00:13:45.270
So I'm going to put a series
of different pictures up there.

00:13:45.270 --> 00:13:47.260
When I put the picture
up, just shout out

00:13:47.260 --> 00:13:49.740
where your eyes go first.

00:13:49.740 --> 00:13:50.550
Ready?

00:13:50.550 --> 00:13:52.470
Where do your eyes
go first here?

00:13:52.470 --> 00:13:53.350
AUDIENCE: Stop.

00:13:53.350 --> 00:13:54.300
COLE NUSSBAUMER KNAFLIC:
Stop sign, right?

00:13:54.300 --> 00:13:56.550
You almost can't look
anywhere else at the onset,

00:13:56.550 --> 00:13:58.190
because it's bright, it's red.

00:13:58.190 --> 00:13:59.940
It's got these big,
bold, capital letters.

00:13:59.940 --> 00:14:02.020
It's outlined in white,
which sets it apart

00:14:02.020 --> 00:14:03.090
from the background.

00:14:03.090 --> 00:14:06.270
We want to think about how
you can use some of those cues

00:14:06.270 --> 00:14:09.385
when you're visualizing data
to draw attention as well.

00:14:09.385 --> 00:14:10.260
Let's do another one.

00:14:10.260 --> 00:14:13.316
Where your eyes go here?

00:14:13.316 --> 00:14:14.570
AUDIENCE: The sun.

00:14:14.570 --> 00:14:15.660
COLE NUSSBAUMER KNAFLIC: Yeah,
if you're like most people,

00:14:15.660 --> 00:14:16.454
they go to the sun.

00:14:16.454 --> 00:14:17.870
But if you're like
me, when you're

00:14:17.870 --> 00:14:19.960
trying to look at the sun,
you get this plane sort

00:14:19.960 --> 00:14:21.930
of tugging on your
peripheral vision.

00:14:21.930 --> 00:14:23.310
Or if I try to
look at the plane,

00:14:23.310 --> 00:14:25.970
I can see the sun sort of
wanting to pull me that way.

00:14:25.970 --> 00:14:27.380
So just be aware
that when you're

00:14:27.380 --> 00:14:31.480
emphasizing multiple things
in a graph or on a page,

00:14:31.480 --> 00:14:34.715
this tension can be
created in your audience.

00:14:34.715 --> 00:14:37.330
How about where do
your eyes go here?

00:14:40.675 --> 00:14:42.050
It depends a little
bit, perhaps,

00:14:42.050 --> 00:14:43.180
on where you're
sitting in the room.

00:14:43.180 --> 00:14:45.640
A lot of people will be
drawn to that Perennial Sale

00:14:45.640 --> 00:14:48.160
sign in bright pink,
because it's bright,

00:14:48.160 --> 00:14:50.380
because of the black,
bold lettering on it.

00:14:50.380 --> 00:14:51.880
And then most people
from there will

00:14:51.880 --> 00:14:54.540
continue down and rightward.

00:14:54.540 --> 00:14:57.250
And that's because,
without other visual cues,

00:14:57.250 --> 00:15:00.635
we typically start at the top
left of our page or our screen

00:15:00.635 --> 00:15:03.130
and do zigzagging Zs across.

00:15:03.130 --> 00:15:05.640
So in this case, that draw to
the Perennial Sale was strong.

00:15:05.640 --> 00:15:09.060
We started there and then
continued on that Z downward

00:15:09.060 --> 00:15:10.250
and to the right.

00:15:10.250 --> 00:15:11.930
Notice that means
we missed whatever

00:15:11.930 --> 00:15:15.260
was happening in the top
left quadrant, and maybe

00:15:15.260 --> 00:15:17.510
that second and third
quadrant as well.

00:15:17.510 --> 00:15:19.690
So to be thoughtful about
the overarching designs

00:15:19.690 --> 00:15:22.760
of the pages on which your
data visualization sits

00:15:22.760 --> 00:15:25.010
and take that into account.

00:15:25.010 --> 00:15:30.230
Just a couple more of these--
where do your eyes go here?

00:15:30.230 --> 00:15:33.180
Everywhere and nowhere
all at the same time.

00:15:33.180 --> 00:15:37.060
Colorful is an awesome
goal for a birthday party.

00:15:37.060 --> 00:15:38.890
Color is not such
an awesome goal

00:15:38.890 --> 00:15:41.230
when it comes to
visualizing data.

00:15:41.230 --> 00:15:42.915
When we make so many
things different,

00:15:42.915 --> 00:15:45.290
we have a lot of stuff competing
for our attention, which

00:15:45.290 --> 00:15:48.960
actually makes it really hard
to look at any one thing.

00:15:48.960 --> 00:15:52.750
Check out the difference in how
your attention is focused here

00:15:52.750 --> 00:15:55.460
versus here, right?

00:15:55.460 --> 00:15:57.100
With the red balloon,
the one thing

00:15:57.100 --> 00:15:58.650
that's different
on the whole page

00:15:58.650 --> 00:16:01.310
we almost can't not look at it.

00:16:01.310 --> 00:16:04.000
That is the power of
color specifically,

00:16:04.000 --> 00:16:06.045
used strategically.

00:16:06.045 --> 00:16:08.290
Let's take a look
now at an example

00:16:08.290 --> 00:16:12.650
from that Project Oxygen study
that I mentioned at the onset.

00:16:12.650 --> 00:16:15.500
This is what one of our
original slides looked like.

00:16:15.500 --> 00:16:17.220
It's been genericized a bit.

00:16:17.220 --> 00:16:19.330
We can see our main
takeaway at the top--

00:16:19.330 --> 00:16:20.920
some elements of
job satisfaction

00:16:20.920 --> 00:16:23.790
are more sensitive to
manager quality than others.

00:16:23.790 --> 00:16:27.660
We've got some categorizations
here and then our data

00:16:27.660 --> 00:16:28.590
at the bottom.

00:16:28.590 --> 00:16:30.840
Here we're not using
color so strategically.

00:16:30.840 --> 00:16:33.329
Here, color is used as a
categorical differentiator.

00:16:33.329 --> 00:16:35.120
There originally, we've
taken them off here

00:16:35.120 --> 00:16:36.736
but were categories
along the bottom.

00:16:36.736 --> 00:16:38.860
You can think of those like
Googlegeist categories,

00:16:38.860 --> 00:16:41.890
things like career development
and performance management

00:16:41.890 --> 00:16:44.660
and culture, which is
not necessarily how

00:16:44.660 --> 00:16:46.740
we want to be using our color.

00:16:46.740 --> 00:16:49.712
So in this case, our
redesign looked like this.

00:16:49.712 --> 00:16:50.920
The graph is mostly the same.

00:16:50.920 --> 00:16:53.640
The contents of the page are
pretty much exactly the same.

00:16:53.640 --> 00:16:55.180
We've just rearranged
things a bit

00:16:55.180 --> 00:16:58.790
and used our pre-attentive
attributes, color specifically,

00:16:58.790 --> 00:17:01.790
more thoughtfully to really
draw our audience's attention

00:17:01.790 --> 00:17:04.499
to where we want them to pay it.

00:17:04.499 --> 00:17:06.040
While we draw
attention, we also want

00:17:06.040 --> 00:17:10.000
to think about embedding
our data in story.

00:17:10.000 --> 00:17:12.697
By way of a Google anecdote,
I can recall a time

00:17:12.697 --> 00:17:14.780
when I was working with
one of the junior analysts

00:17:14.780 --> 00:17:15.829
on our team.

00:17:15.829 --> 00:17:18.780
And she had just finished
analyzing Googlegeist results,

00:17:18.780 --> 00:17:21.430
results from the annual
employee survey [INAUDIBLE] part

00:17:21.430 --> 00:17:22.980
of the organization
and was getting

00:17:22.980 --> 00:17:24.700
ready to communicate
those results

00:17:24.700 --> 00:17:26.425
to the leader of that team.

00:17:26.425 --> 00:17:27.800
And this particular
team had been

00:17:27.800 --> 00:17:29.310
struggling in a lot of places.

00:17:29.310 --> 00:17:30.580
The scores weren't great.

00:17:30.580 --> 00:17:33.570
So there was some sensitivity
around how that message should

00:17:33.570 --> 00:17:34.850
be delivered.

00:17:34.850 --> 00:17:37.610
And the deck at
that point was page

00:17:37.610 --> 00:17:41.690
after page after page
of the standard report--

00:17:41.690 --> 00:17:45.480
no story and little narrative
to tie it all together.

00:17:45.480 --> 00:17:47.950
It would have been very easy
for the leader of that group

00:17:47.950 --> 00:17:50.070
to say, well,
that's interesting,

00:17:50.070 --> 00:17:51.890
and move on to the next thing.

00:17:51.890 --> 00:17:53.550
That would have been a failure.

00:17:53.550 --> 00:17:56.690
So what I had the analyst do was
set the deck aside and tell me

00:17:56.690 --> 00:17:57.420
the story.

00:17:57.420 --> 00:18:00.720
Tell me what you learned when
you were analyzing this data.

00:18:00.720 --> 00:18:03.810
And when we did that, the
articulation of the story

00:18:03.810 --> 00:18:05.370
was super powerful.

00:18:05.370 --> 00:18:07.020
There were clear
areas for improvement,

00:18:07.020 --> 00:18:09.040
and she knew exactly
where to focus action

00:18:09.040 --> 00:18:11.420
to achieve that improvement.

00:18:11.420 --> 00:18:13.250
This we could use
to light a fire

00:18:13.250 --> 00:18:15.430
under the leader for that team.

00:18:15.430 --> 00:18:18.750
So it's a good example
of how data without story

00:18:18.750 --> 00:18:20.470
isn't always so meaningful.

00:18:20.470 --> 00:18:24.090
But the story can help
bring the data to life.

00:18:24.090 --> 00:18:27.450
So we want to think about how
we can leverage that power when

00:18:27.450 --> 00:18:32.040
we are communicating with data
every time we're doing it.

00:18:32.040 --> 00:18:34.810
Here are some facts on a slide.

00:18:34.810 --> 00:18:36.580
Go ahead and read through these.

00:18:45.060 --> 00:18:47.309
Anybody recognize what
we're looking at here?

00:18:47.309 --> 00:18:48.100
What story is this?

00:18:51.020 --> 00:18:53.350
Red Riding Hood, right?

00:18:53.350 --> 00:18:58.330
But facts on a slide are not
so compelling or memorable.

00:18:58.330 --> 00:19:00.770
If I ask you a day
or two from now,

00:19:00.770 --> 00:19:02.780
what distance was it
from Red Riding Hood's

00:19:02.780 --> 00:19:06.556
house to grandma's, or what time
did Red Riding Hood get there,

00:19:06.556 --> 00:19:08.180
these aren't likely
facts that you will

00:19:08.180 --> 00:19:10.550
have committed to your memory.

00:19:10.550 --> 00:19:13.760
Stories, on the other
hand, are memorable.

00:19:13.760 --> 00:19:15.510
How many people--
quick show of hands--

00:19:15.510 --> 00:19:18.690
know the story of
Red Riding Hood?

00:19:18.690 --> 00:19:20.170
Pretty much everybody
in the room.

00:19:20.170 --> 00:19:21.794
We'll do a quick
thought exercise here.

00:19:21.794 --> 00:19:23.340
We'll just take
about 15 seconds.

00:19:23.340 --> 00:19:25.760
Close your eyes, or
stare up at this screen,

00:19:25.760 --> 00:19:29.260
and I'd like you to recall
for yourself the story of Reg

00:19:29.260 --> 00:19:31.270
Riding Hood,
thinking specifically

00:19:31.270 --> 00:19:35.300
about the plot, the twists, and
the ending-- 15 seconds here.

00:19:51.079 --> 00:19:52.620
Quick show of hands--
how many people

00:19:52.620 --> 00:19:54.790
were able to get to
the high level story?

00:19:54.790 --> 00:19:57.040
People are always a little
afraid to raise their hands

00:19:57.040 --> 00:20:00.560
at this point for fear of
what might happen next.

00:20:00.560 --> 00:20:01.180
Bear with me.

00:20:01.180 --> 00:20:04.710
I'll tell you the story
that resides in my head.

00:20:04.710 --> 00:20:05.964
So Red Riding Hood sets off.

00:20:05.964 --> 00:20:07.130
She has a basket of goodies.

00:20:07.130 --> 00:20:08.171
She's going to Grandma's.

00:20:08.171 --> 00:20:09.430
Grandma's not feeling well.

00:20:09.430 --> 00:20:12.220
And on her way, she
encounters a wolf.

00:20:12.220 --> 00:20:14.190
The wold is able to
extract from her where

00:20:14.190 --> 00:20:17.420
she's going and realizes
that if he's patient,

00:20:17.420 --> 00:20:19.790
he can have not only
one dinner, but two.

00:20:19.790 --> 00:20:24.050
So he races ahead to Grandma's,
eats Grandma, and dress up

00:20:24.050 --> 00:20:25.600
in her clothes,
get into her bed.

00:20:25.600 --> 00:20:28.790
Red Riding Hood arrives
and senses something

00:20:28.790 --> 00:20:30.830
is awry and goes
through a series

00:20:30.830 --> 00:20:34.120
of questioning with the
wolf posing as Grandma.

00:20:34.120 --> 00:20:36.530
Oh, Grandma, how
big your eyes are.

00:20:36.530 --> 00:20:38.490
Oh, Grandma, how
big your ears are.

00:20:38.490 --> 00:20:43.710
Oh, Grandma, how big your teeth
are, to which the wold replies?

00:20:43.710 --> 00:20:45.560
All the better to eat you with.

00:20:45.560 --> 00:20:49.310
So the wolf actually eats
Red Riding Hood as well.

00:20:49.310 --> 00:20:52.690
But then guy with an ax shows
up, cuts open the wolf's belly,

00:20:52.690 --> 00:20:55.600
and the wolf had eaten
Grandma and Red in such haste

00:20:55.600 --> 00:20:56.370
that they're fine.

00:20:56.370 --> 00:20:57.780
They come out.

00:20:57.780 --> 00:21:00.820
And interestingly, if you go
back to the Grimm's original,

00:21:00.820 --> 00:21:02.060
the wolf doesn't die then.

00:21:02.060 --> 00:21:03.810
They actually fill
his stomach with rocks

00:21:03.810 --> 00:21:08.200
and sew him up so that when
he wakes up, he drops dead.

00:21:08.200 --> 00:21:11.530
I think it's a warning
story-- go straight where

00:21:11.530 --> 00:21:13.770
you're intended to go,
don't talk to strangers,

00:21:13.770 --> 00:21:15.310
and so forth.

00:21:15.310 --> 00:21:16.970
But what does this
tell us about what

00:21:16.970 --> 00:21:18.440
we're here to talk about today?

00:21:18.440 --> 00:21:20.820
So for me, stories
like Red Riding Hood

00:21:20.820 --> 00:21:22.800
are evidence of a
couple of things.

00:21:22.800 --> 00:21:25.350
First off is the
power of repetition,

00:21:25.350 --> 00:21:27.940
when you consider it's probably
been some amount of time

00:21:27.940 --> 00:21:30.800
since you've given much thought
to the story of Red Riding

00:21:30.800 --> 00:21:31.470
Hood.

00:21:31.470 --> 00:21:33.990
And yet over the course
of time, you've perhaps

00:21:33.990 --> 00:21:35.940
heard that story
a number of times,

00:21:35.940 --> 00:21:38.650
read the story a number of
times, maybe told the story

00:21:38.650 --> 00:21:40.150
a number of times.

00:21:40.150 --> 00:21:43.220
There's something that happens
with that repetition of use,

00:21:43.220 --> 00:21:46.750
of hearing and saying and
reading things multiple times,

00:21:46.750 --> 00:21:49.440
that helps form a bridge
from our short-term memory

00:21:49.440 --> 00:21:51.250
to our long-term memory.

00:21:51.250 --> 00:21:53.500
The other cool thing that
stories like Red Riding Hood

00:21:53.500 --> 00:21:57.510
illustrate for us is this
magical combination of plot

00:21:57.510 --> 00:21:59.890
and twists and
ending that enable

00:21:59.890 --> 00:22:03.340
things to stick with us in a
way that we can later recall

00:22:03.340 --> 00:22:05.925
and retell to somebody else.

00:22:05.925 --> 00:22:07.800
So we want to think
about how we can leverage

00:22:07.800 --> 00:22:10.410
these powerful concepts
when it comes to the stories

00:22:10.410 --> 00:22:12.710
that we want to
tell with our data

00:22:12.710 --> 00:22:15.910
to get those to be something our
audience will remember in a way

00:22:15.910 --> 00:22:19.960
that they can later recall
and retell to somebody else.

00:22:19.960 --> 00:22:22.631
So when we think about the
components of the story,

00:22:22.631 --> 00:22:24.380
we want to think back
to those same things

00:22:24.380 --> 00:22:26.880
that we talked about with
Red Riding Hood-- the plot,

00:22:26.880 --> 00:22:28.550
the twists, the ending.

00:22:28.550 --> 00:22:32.210
The plot becomes what context
is essential for your audience.

00:22:32.210 --> 00:22:33.852
What do they need
to know in order

00:22:33.852 --> 00:22:35.560
to be in the right
frame of mind for what

00:22:35.560 --> 00:22:37.590
you're going to tell them?

00:22:37.590 --> 00:22:40.010
Then the twists-- what's
interesting about the data

00:22:40.010 --> 00:22:41.640
and what it shows?

00:22:41.640 --> 00:22:43.690
By the way, if
there isn't anything

00:22:43.690 --> 00:22:47.299
interesting about the
data, don't show the data.

00:22:47.299 --> 00:22:49.840
You run the risk of losing your
audience's attention for when

00:22:49.840 --> 00:22:52.810
you do have something
important to say with it.

00:22:52.810 --> 00:22:54.970
And then finally, the
ending, the call to action--

00:22:54.970 --> 00:22:57.340
what do you want
your audience to do?

00:22:57.340 --> 00:23:01.260
My view is we should always want
our audience to do something.

00:23:01.260 --> 00:23:03.550
And we should be working
to make that something as

00:23:03.550 --> 00:23:05.680
clear as possible.

00:23:05.680 --> 00:23:08.400
Because if we simply show
data, as we saw in that case

00:23:08.400 --> 00:23:10.720
with the Googlegeist deck,
it's easy for our audience

00:23:10.720 --> 00:23:13.560
to say, oh, that's interesting,
and move on to the next thing.

00:23:13.560 --> 00:23:16.200
But if we ask for
action, our audience

00:23:16.200 --> 00:23:17.810
has to respond to that.

00:23:17.810 --> 00:23:20.430
And even if they disagree,
it starts a conversation.

00:23:20.430 --> 00:23:21.850
And it's a
conversation may never

00:23:21.850 --> 00:23:24.900
happen if we simply show data.

00:23:24.900 --> 00:23:27.310
Let's take a look at an example.

00:23:27.310 --> 00:23:29.330
So in this scenario,
imagine that you just

00:23:29.330 --> 00:23:31.800
wrapped up a summer
learning program on science.

00:23:31.800 --> 00:23:35.350
The goal was to get kids
excited about science.

00:23:35.350 --> 00:23:37.270
We have some survey
data from a survey

00:23:37.270 --> 00:23:39.220
we gave before the
program on the left

00:23:39.220 --> 00:23:41.820
and after the program on the
right, where children could

00:23:41.820 --> 00:23:44.670
classify their interest
as Bored, Not Great, OK,

00:23:44.670 --> 00:23:46.550
Kind of Interested, and Excited.

00:23:46.550 --> 00:23:48.570
I'll give you moment
to take this in,

00:23:48.570 --> 00:23:49.892
and then we'll talk about it.

00:23:56.030 --> 00:24:00.340
How's it feel comparing
segments across two pies?

00:24:00.340 --> 00:24:03.410
Not so great, right?

00:24:03.410 --> 00:24:07.425
The only thing worse than
a pie, for me personally?

00:24:07.425 --> 00:24:10.050
Two pies, especially when you're
trying to compare across them.

00:24:10.050 --> 00:24:12.280
Because if anything changed in
the data, which it should have

00:24:12.280 --> 00:24:14.390
if there's something interesting
you're trying to say,

00:24:14.390 --> 00:24:16.431
the pieces are all in an
entirely different place

00:24:16.431 --> 00:24:17.437
over there on the right.

00:24:17.437 --> 00:24:19.020
So you always want
to think about what

00:24:19.020 --> 00:24:20.740
do you want to allow
your audience to compare.

00:24:20.740 --> 00:24:22.823
How do you align those
things to a common baseline

00:24:22.823 --> 00:24:25.930
and put them as close
together as possible.

00:24:25.930 --> 00:24:30.000
But check out what happens if I
talk you through the narrative.

00:24:30.000 --> 00:24:32.270
So going into the program,
the biggest segment

00:24:32.270 --> 00:24:36.500
of students is 40% in green
felt just OK about science,

00:24:36.500 --> 00:24:39.290
maybe hadn't made up their
minds one way or the other.

00:24:39.290 --> 00:24:42.130
Whereas after the program, a
really cool thing happened.

00:24:42.130 --> 00:24:46.296
That great big 40%
shrunk down to only 14%.

00:24:46.296 --> 00:24:47.920
Now, there was a
little bit of movement

00:24:47.920 --> 00:24:49.660
in the negative direction.

00:24:49.660 --> 00:24:52.430
Bored and Not Great went
up a percentage point each.

00:24:52.430 --> 00:24:55.510
But most of the movement was in
the positive direction, wherein

00:24:55.510 --> 00:24:59.040
after the program, nearly 70%
of kids, if we add together

00:24:59.040 --> 00:25:01.850
that purple and teal
segments, expressed interest

00:25:01.850 --> 00:25:03.650
towards science.

00:25:03.650 --> 00:25:05.190
This is a successful program.

00:25:05.190 --> 00:25:07.770
We should continue to offer it.

00:25:07.770 --> 00:25:10.330
Notice how with a
strong narrative,

00:25:10.330 --> 00:25:13.550
I can actually get away with
a kind of crummy visual.

00:25:13.550 --> 00:25:15.420
The alternative
does not hold true.

00:25:15.420 --> 00:25:17.960
I can have the most
beautiful data visualization

00:25:17.960 --> 00:25:21.414
in the world, and without a
compelling story to go with it,

00:25:21.414 --> 00:25:22.830
to make my audience
care about it,

00:25:22.830 --> 00:25:24.954
to make it something that
resonates with them, that

00:25:24.954 --> 00:25:27.660
sticks with them, I run the
risk of that beautiful data

00:25:27.660 --> 00:25:30.117
visualization falling flat.

00:25:30.117 --> 00:25:31.950
So that's not to say
we shouldn't spend time

00:25:31.950 --> 00:25:33.570
perfecting our
data visualization,

00:25:33.570 --> 00:25:37.710
but rather to underscore
the importance of story.

00:25:37.710 --> 00:25:39.160
And now, nirvana
in this stuff is

00:25:39.160 --> 00:25:41.160
reached when both
are strong-- you

00:25:41.160 --> 00:25:45.510
have a powerful story and an
effective visual to back it up.

00:25:45.510 --> 00:25:48.150
So in this case, we could end up
somewhere like this-- Exposure

00:25:48.150 --> 00:25:50.350
to science excites kids.

00:25:50.350 --> 00:25:52.450
A bit of background,
our call to action,

00:25:52.450 --> 00:25:53.900
let's keep offering this.

00:25:53.900 --> 00:25:55.650
Then we get down to the data.

00:25:55.650 --> 00:25:57.250
How do you feel about science?

00:25:57.250 --> 00:26:00.520
Beforehand, most kids
tied through both color

00:26:00.520 --> 00:26:03.530
and proximity to the data point
that is evidence of that point.

00:26:03.530 --> 00:26:04.936
Most kids felt OK.

00:26:04.936 --> 00:26:06.310
Whereas after the
program, we get

00:26:06.310 --> 00:26:08.304
this pull to the
right-hand side,

00:26:08.304 --> 00:26:09.720
where kids are
feeling interested.

00:26:09.720 --> 00:26:13.240
They're feeling
excited about science.

00:26:13.240 --> 00:26:14.870
That's the kind of
story that we want

00:26:14.870 --> 00:26:16.790
to create for our audience.

00:26:16.790 --> 00:26:19.890
That's the way we want to
be able to focus attention

00:26:19.890 --> 00:26:22.340
for our audience.

00:26:22.340 --> 00:26:24.740
So those are the
quick lessons I have

00:26:24.740 --> 00:26:26.334
to cover here with you today.

00:26:26.334 --> 00:26:27.750
I wanted to give
you a quick sense

00:26:27.750 --> 00:26:30.700
of how they fit in with the
rest of the content in the book.

00:26:30.700 --> 00:26:33.870
So I've listed out
the chapters here.

00:26:33.870 --> 00:26:37.310
Chapter 1 starts off
with a lesson on context,

00:26:37.310 --> 00:26:38.870
having a really
clear understanding

00:26:38.870 --> 00:26:42.929
of who your audience is and
what you want them to know or do

00:26:42.929 --> 00:26:44.470
