00:35:43.230 --> 00:35:46.379
But some sources of
consistently good work

00:35:46.379 --> 00:35:48.670
are places like-- we talked
about the "New York Times,"

00:35:48.670 --> 00:35:50.940
the "Wall Street Journal."
"National Geographic"

00:35:50.940 --> 00:35:54.530
does some really great
data visualizations.

00:35:54.530 --> 00:35:57.385
When it comes to
tools in particular,

00:35:57.385 --> 00:35:58.760
everything we
looked at today was

00:35:58.760 --> 00:36:01.430
Excel, which is what I
find myself using primarily

00:36:01.430 --> 00:36:04.970
because it's what most
of my clients use.

00:36:04.970 --> 00:36:07.170
Tableau is certainly
increasingly popular.

00:36:07.170 --> 00:36:10.340
My view is you should
find a tool, pick a tool,

00:36:10.340 --> 00:36:12.200
and get to know
it as best you can

00:36:12.200 --> 00:36:14.170
so that it doesn't
become a limiting factor

00:36:14.170 --> 00:36:16.780
in applying some of the things
that we talked about today.

00:36:16.780 --> 00:36:20.989
Any tool can be used well, and
any tool can be used poorly.

00:36:20.989 --> 00:36:22.530
And the cool things
about the lessons

00:36:22.530 --> 00:36:24.240
we went through today and
the lessons in the book

00:36:24.240 --> 00:36:25.970
is they're not specific
to any given tool.

00:36:25.970 --> 00:36:26.886
They're tool agnostic.

00:36:26.886 --> 00:36:29.310
They are foundational
principles that you can apply

00:36:29.310 --> 00:36:32.410
in varying extent in any tool.

