00:38:00.310 --> 00:38:02.450
AUDIENCE: My question is,
if we have a lot of data

00:38:02.450 --> 00:38:05.130
that we want to show, like
there are lots of key insights

00:38:05.130 --> 00:38:07.270
that we want to pull,
would you suggest

00:38:07.270 --> 00:38:09.776
that we try to parse them
out into different pieces?

00:38:09.776 --> 00:38:11.650
Or do you have a
recommendation for something

00:38:11.650 --> 00:38:13.430
that we could use
to kind of point

00:38:13.430 --> 00:38:15.500
out all the different insights?

00:38:15.500 --> 00:38:15.830
COLE NUSSBAUMER
KNAFLIC: Yeah, I have

00:38:15.830 --> 00:38:17.038
a couple of thoughts on that.

00:38:17.038 --> 00:38:20.140
So one thought is when you
have a lot of different things

00:38:20.140 --> 00:38:21.890
you want to say about
the same data set is

00:38:21.890 --> 00:38:26.100
to step back and figure out,
is there an overarching story

00:38:26.100 --> 00:38:28.980
that you can use to weave
all of those disparate pieces

00:38:28.980 --> 00:38:29.740
together?

00:38:29.740 --> 00:38:32.910
So as we talked about, that's
one way of really making

00:38:32.910 --> 00:38:35.060
it memorable for your audience.

00:38:35.060 --> 00:38:38.650
A specific strategy you can
use, depending on the situation,

00:38:38.650 --> 00:38:41.980
is something similar to what we
looked at with that generic bar

00:38:41.980 --> 00:38:45.086
graph from the
customer survey, where

00:38:45.086 --> 00:38:46.460
if you're showing
a bunch of data

00:38:46.460 --> 00:38:48.793
and you want to be able to
talk your audience through it

00:38:48.793 --> 00:38:50.920
but then focus on one
specific thing at a time,

00:38:50.920 --> 00:38:52.610
you can start off
with just the data,

00:38:52.610 --> 00:38:54.620
or even just a blank
graph sometimes

00:38:54.620 --> 00:38:58.130
that has the axes labeled and
titled but no actual data.

00:38:58.130 --> 00:39:00.750
Explain to your audience what
they're going to be looking at.

00:39:00.750 --> 00:39:02.260
Then you layer on the data.

00:39:02.260 --> 00:39:04.955
And then you maybe use
color or another visual cue

00:39:04.955 --> 00:39:06.830
to draw your audience's
attention to one part

00:39:06.830 --> 00:39:07.950
and talk about that.

00:39:07.950 --> 00:39:10.950
Then draw attention to another
part, and then talk about that.

00:39:10.950 --> 00:39:13.480
It's a nice way of it being
able to build familiarity

00:39:13.480 --> 00:39:16.640
with the data with your
audience as you talk through it

00:39:16.640 --> 00:39:18.480
and then also focus
attention really

00:39:18.480 --> 00:39:21.050
specifically within
that broader data set

00:39:21.050 --> 00:39:24.050
when you have specific things
you want to say about it.

00:39:24.050 --> 00:39:25.310
Great question.

00:39:25.310 --> 00:39:27.370
TINA MALM: Let me
ask you one more.

00:39:27.370 --> 00:39:29.520
Your opinions about
green-- I noticed

00:39:29.520 --> 00:39:31.692
that you didn't use any
green on the slides.

00:39:31.692 --> 00:39:33.650
COLE NUSSBAUMER KNAFLIC:
Oh, interesting point.

00:39:33.650 --> 00:39:36.500
So that was by accident
probably more than intentional.

00:39:36.500 --> 00:39:38.070
Although back on
the topic of color,

00:39:38.070 --> 00:39:39.611
one thing you want
to be sensitive to

00:39:39.611 --> 00:39:40.980
is color blindness.

00:39:40.980 --> 00:39:43.940
So roughly 8% of men and
half a percent of women

00:39:43.940 --> 00:39:46.710
experience some form
of color blindness.

00:39:46.710 --> 00:39:48.210
Most typically that
manifests itself

00:39:48.210 --> 00:39:50.430
as difficulty in
distinguishing between shades

00:39:50.430 --> 00:39:52.390
of red and shades
of green, which

00:39:52.390 --> 00:39:55.460
means you want to, in general,
avoid using shades of red

00:39:55.460 --> 00:39:56.921
and shades of green together.

00:39:56.921 --> 00:39:59.170
Or if you want to leverage
that connotation, green, it

00:39:59.170 --> 00:40:00.330
went up-- that's good--
red, it went down--

00:40:00.330 --> 00:40:01.900
that's bad-- you can do so.

00:40:01.900 --> 00:40:04.880
Just make sure you have some
additional visual cues there.

00:40:04.880 --> 00:40:06.090
Make the numbers also bold.

00:40:06.090 --> 00:40:07.923
Put the plus or minus
sign in front of them.

00:40:07.923 --> 00:40:09.790
Do something else to
set them apart visually

00:40:09.790 --> 00:40:11.670
so you're not inadvertently
disenfranchising

00:40:11.670 --> 00:40:12.930
part of your audience.

00:40:12.930 --> 00:40:16.550
Personally, I tend to do
my designs mostly in gray

00:40:16.550 --> 00:40:19.680
and then use blue really
sparingly to draw tension.

00:40:19.680 --> 00:40:22.000
I like blue because you
avoid the color blind issues.

00:40:22.000 --> 00:40:25.100
It also prints well in black
and white if that's a concern.

00:40:25.100 --> 00:40:29.770
But that said, blue is
certainly not your only option.

00:40:29.770 --> 00:40:32.010
So we talked about the
tones of different colors.

00:40:32.010 --> 00:40:34.510
You want to think about brand
colors and all of these things

00:40:34.510 --> 00:40:38.626
and how those can fold into
how you visualize your data.

