COLE NUSSBAUMER
KNAFLIC: It's really

00:43:47.530 --> 00:43:49.610
anybody who has a need
to communicate with data,

00:43:49.610 --> 00:43:53.120
so whether that's working with
data on a daily basis or less

00:43:53.120 --> 00:43:53.970
frequently.

00:43:53.970 --> 00:43:56.360
And the concepts
that we talk about,

00:43:56.360 --> 00:43:58.844
or that I talk about in
the book, the examples

00:43:58.844 --> 00:44:00.510
are specific to data,
for the most part,

00:44:00.510 --> 00:44:03.410
but really it's any time you
need to communicate visually

00:44:03.410 --> 00:44:04.700
to an audience.

00:44:04.700 --> 00:44:06.760
And a lot of it goes
back to really thinking

00:44:06.760 --> 00:44:09.390
about who your
audience is and how

00:44:09.390 --> 00:44:11.902
you want them to use the
information that you're putting

00:44:11.902 --> 00:44:14.110
in front of them and then
just designing thoughtfully

00:44:14.110 --> 00:44:15.366
with that in mind.

00:44:15.366 --> 00:44:16.740
DAVEY NICKELS:
Cole, one question

00:44:16.740 --> 00:44:17.930
