00:44:38.820 --> 00:44:39.550
Yeah, absolutely.

00:44:39.550 --> 00:44:42.610
Data viz is a really
fun community.

00:44:42.610 --> 00:44:44.490
It's relatively close-knit.

00:44:44.490 --> 00:44:46.324
The main players all
sort of know each other

00:44:46.324 --> 00:44:48.614
or know of each other, and
we have some correspondence.

00:44:48.614 --> 00:44:50.360
And one of the things
that's really cool

00:44:50.360 --> 00:44:53.950
is that there's really a
lot of open sharing, right?

00:44:53.950 --> 00:44:55.840
Because the goal is to
make everybody better,

00:44:55.840 --> 00:44:58.550
everybody more
effective at this stuff.

00:44:58.550 --> 00:45:01.570
But one particular
disagreement-- so Robert Kosara

00:45:01.570 --> 00:45:06.510
is one of the main data
visualization researcher guys

00:45:06.510 --> 00:45:07.740
at Tableau.

00:45:07.740 --> 00:45:11.610
And he was actually one of
the reviewers on my book.

00:45:11.610 --> 00:45:16.660
And he disagrees that pie
charts are inherently evil.

00:45:16.660 --> 00:45:20.880
And so he and I have had
some decent debate on this.

00:45:20.880 --> 00:45:23.700
My view is relatively
strong, that pie charts,

00:45:23.700 --> 00:45:25.369
you can say some
general things, right?

00:45:25.369 --> 00:45:27.160
This segment is big,
this segment is small.

00:45:27.160 --> 00:45:29.618
